                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>18.772</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>064000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                    <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#chamoux1953"/>, p. <citedRange>214, footnote 8</citedRange></bibl>
                    whence <bibl><ptr target="#robertBE"/>, <citedRange>1954.278</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#manganaro1989"/><citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>39.1680</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#manganaro1990"/>, p. 426, n. <citedRange>71</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>40.1594</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#ottone2000"/><citedRange/></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>50.1629</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#gill2004"/>, p. <citedRange>391</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>54.1778</citedRange></bibl>;
                        <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, pp. <citedRange>232-233</citedRange>, number 2 (text)</bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><rs type="office" key="ephoros"><w lemma="ἔφορος">Ἐφόρων</w></rs> καὶ <rs type="office" key="geron"><w lemma="γέρων">γερόντων</w></rs>
                    <lb n="2"/><w lemma="ἐπάγω">ἐπαγόντων</w>, <w lemma="ἁνδάνω">ἇδε</w> τᾶι <rs type="office" key="boule"><w lemma="βωλά">βωλᾶι</w></rs>
                    <lb n="3"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V3a-38549"><name nymRef="#Εὔβιος">Εὔβιον</name> 
                        <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V3a-38551"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Εὐβίοτος">Εὐβιότω</name></persName></persName>, 
                        <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V3a-37093"><name nymRef="Ἁγέστρατος">Ἁγέστ<lb n="4" break="no"/>ρατον</name>
                            <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V3a-40042"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Μοσχίων">Μοσχίωνος</name></persName></persName>, 
                        <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="#Συρακόσιος">Συρ<lb n="5" break="no"/>ρακοσίος</placeName>, <placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="#Εὐσπερίτας">Εὐσπεριτᾶν</placeName>
                    <lb n="6"/><rs type="office" key="proxenos"><w lemma="πρόξενος">πρoξένος</w></rs> <w lemma="εἰμι">ἦμεν</w> <w lemma="αὐτός">αὐτὸς</w>
                    <lb n="7"/>καὶ <w lemma="ἔκγονος">ἐκγόνος</w>.

	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> Sur proposition des éphores et des <foreign rend="italic">gérontes</foreign>, le conseil a décidé:
            qu'Eubios fils d'Eubiôtos et Agestratos fils de Moskhiôn, de Syracuse, soient proxènes des Euhespéritains, eux-mêmes et leurs descendants.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> The <foreign rend="italic">ephoroi</foreign> and the <foreign rend="italic">gerontes</foreign> having proposed, the council decided:
            that Eubios son of Eubiotos and Agestratos son of Moschion, from Syracusae, would be <foreign rend="italic">proxenoi</foreign> of the Euesperitans, themselves and their offspring.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> Su proposta degli efori e dei <foreign rend="italic">gerontes</foreign>, il consiglio ha deciso: 
                che Eubios figlio di Eubiotos e Agestratos figlio di Moschion, di Siracusa, siano prosseni degli Euesperitani, loro e i loro discendenti.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This is the only official document known to us from the city of Euesperides. It gives useful informations about its institutions, with a council and 
                <foreign rend="italic">ephoroi</foreign> taking part in the decision. It is also the only proxeny mentioned in the Cyrenaican inscriptions, in contrast with a series of 
                    citizens from various cities in Cyrenaica being granted proxeny by foreing cities.</p>
	           <p>The stone, originating from Euesperides, was published from a photograph by Fraser, who thought that it was lost. However, C. Dobias-Lalou could see it in 1976 at Cyrene, 
               	where it was evidently brought as a consequence of the multiple movings of World War II.</p>
	           <p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
